      <p>where <italic>Q</italic> is a variational distribution for the approximate of the posterior <italic>p</italic>(<italic>h</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>|<italic>V</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>). We constrain <italic>Q</italic> to the family of rectified and normalized Gaussian distributions. <italic>D</italic><sub><italic>KL</italic></sub> &gt; 0 is the KL distance. ùîΩ is the objective of the EM algorithm. The E-step maximizes ùîΩ with respect to <italic>Q</italic>; therefore, the E-step minimizes <italic>D</italic><sub><italic>KL</italic></sub>(<italic>Q</italic>(<italic>h</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>|<italic>V</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>)||<italic>p</italic>(<italic>h</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>|<italic>V</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>)). The M-step maximizes ùîΩ respect to the parameters (<italic>W</italic>, Œ•); therefore, the M-step maximizes ‚à´<italic>Q</italic>(<italic>h</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>|<italic>V</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>)log<italic>p</italic>(<italic>V</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>|<italic>h</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>)<italic>dh</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>. Considering the quadratic problem of the posterior regularization method, to speed up the computation using fast GPU implementations, we perform a gradient step in both E- and M-steps. In the E-step, we use the projected Newton method as in Equation (5).</p>
